  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">FREEDM: Flood Resilient Environmentally Enhanced Disaster Management</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. To establish community led disaster preparedness systems in all the 20 hamlets covering 2,910 direct and 16,000 indirect beneficiaries in each of Saharsa and Muzaffarpur districts through improved local level preparedness plans, creation of local cash and food reserves and capacity building of local cadre of people in 18 months of project period.   

2. To create resilient livelihoods through cultivation of flood resistant crops, water body reclamation, demonstrating bio-shield (Bamboo and Banana plantation) and social security (insurance) in 18 months of project period.

3. To improve access to government services and entitlements meant for Disaster Prone Areas through establishment of 2 Citizens Forum at the district level (two total, one in each district) and plans for community engagement for effective govt. delivery system in 20 hamlets in Saharsa and Muzaffarpur districts.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Saharsa and Muzaffarpur districts of Bihar State,communities lack the capacity to cope with and recover from annual flooding that disproportionately impacts marginalized populations. Communities also do not have community-based disaster preparedness systems&#x2014;such as an early warning system&#x2014;food and fodder reserve and cash reserves, which results in a recurring loss of crops, livestock and shelter. In addition, communities have limited access to government services and entitlements that are meant for disaster-prone populations, such as those in Saharsa and Muzaffarpur districts.

In response, LWR aims to increase the resilience to annual flooding of 10 targeted villages in Saharsa and Muzaffarpur districts.

The project plans to directly engage 2,910 people in the formation of community-led disaster management committees, creation of resilient livelihood opportunities and improved community engagement in government services.</narrative>
  </description>
